<!channel> congratulations for finishing up class last night! I hope you all had a great experience and learned a lot. A few quick housekeeping items: 
1) This slack channel will stay open and available to you through Wednesday, July 5th - please collect any information and exchange contact info before it closes!; 
2) Please feel welcome to stay connected with <@U38KEPD62> and I for technical questions or questions about next steps in your learning journey; 
3) I would love to connect with each of you 1:1 to support you in continuing to learn - please book some time on my calendar (<http://laurenlark.youcanbook.me|laurenlark.youcanbook.me>) for us to connect. I'll reach out to those I don't hear from via email in a week or so. 
4) You will be receiving a quick survey in the next day or 2 about your experience in the class. Please reach out to <@U5BJR2HV1> (<mailto:bethany.lindsey@galvanize.com|bethany.lindsey@galvanize.com>) if you have any questions about this OR for any certificate of completion requests; 
5) Have an awesome 4th of July and rest of your summers! :flag-us: :sunny: :galvanize:

<!channel> Hey everyone! In preparation for class tonight I’d like everyone to get as far as they can in the exercise titled *Functions with Arrays and Objects*. We will start off class with some time to work on this and review any other concepts covered so far. Additionally we will be starting a mini-project (hangman game) so if you’re curious you can read ahead in chapter 7 of _JS for Kids_. See you all tonight!
Okay, got it. I am on mobile, a little hard to see. Thank you very much!
Initially, I only have this `var obj3 = Object.assign({}, obj1, obj2)` but it gave me the `Expected undefined to equal Object({ a: 1 }).` so I added the if statement.
I thought that it wants me to give a default value of {a: 1} if either obj1 || obj2 is empty.
I also believe that the if statement above is unnecessary
The error `Expected undefined` happens because nothing was returned in the function so it defaulted to undefined
<@U56E8G0LC> This part of your solution looks good: `var obj3 = Object.assign({}, obj1, obj2)`
I keep getting this while doing the “combine” problem in Functions with Arrays and Objects
<@U38KEPD62> did you want us to do any reading???
perhaps just create a counter that records how many valid numbers you have found. The test doesn’t care about actual values, just wether or not the string has 10 numbers total
The best thing to do is to not splice the `phoneArray` variable directly
The values being skipped is due to the fact that you alter (splice) the array while you are in the middle of looping over it

There are two ‘bugs’ we can fix here. The first is with the usage of `isNaN`. You correctly parse the value from the array (`var num = parseInt(phoneArray[i]);`), but in the if statement you call `isNaN` on the original value in the array, not the newly parsed `num` variable
Would you mind posting the code for the surrounding loop?
Hmm that is odd. `phoneArray.splice(i, 1)` should just remove 1 value at index `i`
Could you explain what’s going on here, please!
